{{Infobox samurai | name = Shōni Sukeyoshi (少弐 資能) | image = | imagesize = | caption = | era = Early to mid-[[Kamakura period]] | birth_date = [[Kenkyū]] 9 (1198) | death_date = [[Kōan]] 4, intercalary [[7th month]], [[13th day (lunar calendar)|13th day]] (August 28, 1281) | posthumous_name = Kakue (覚恵; Dharma name) | alias = Muto Sukeyoshi | rank = [[Dazai Shōni|Assistant Governor of Dazaifu]] | allegiance = [[Kamakura shogunate]] | lord = [[Fujiwara no Yoritsune|Yoritsune]], [[Fujiwara no Yoritsugu|Yoritsugu]], [[Prince Munetaka]], [[Prince Koreyasu]] | clan = {{ill|Shōni clan|ja|少弐氏|12=draft|12=draft}} | parents = Father: {{ill|Muto Sukeyori|ja|武藤資頼|12=draft|12=draft}} | siblings = Sukeyoshi, {{ill|Muto Yorishige|ja|武藤頼茂|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Muto Tameyori|ja|武藤為頼|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Muto Yorimoto|ja|武藤頼基|12=draft|12=draft}} | spouse = | children = {{ill|Shōni Kyonori|ja|少弐経資|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shōni Kagesue|ja|少弐景資|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shōni Morisue|ja|少弐盛資|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="sonpibunmyaku">『尊卑分脈』第2篇・391頁。</ref>, {{ill|Shōni Munetsune|ja|少弐宗資|12=draft|12=draft}}? | notable = }}
'''Shōni Sukeyoshi''' (少弐 資能) was a [[samurai]] and retainer of the [[Kamakura shogunate]] active during the early to mid-[[Kamakura period]]. He was the second head of the {{ill|Shōni clan|ja|少弐氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Biography ==
During Sukeyoshi’s time, the {{ill|Muto clan|ja|武藤氏|12=draft|12=draft}} held the position of [[Dazai Shōni]], a role associated with governance in the {{ill|Dazaifu|ja|大宰府|12=draft|12=draft}} region. This responsibility led to the family adopting the surname {{ill|Shōni|ja|少弐氏|12=draft|12=draft}} starting from Sukeyoshi’s generation.
Sukeyoshi wielded significant power in northern Kyushu and served as the shogunate's {{ill|Chinzei Bugyō|ja|鎮西奉行|12=draft|12=draft}}. In [[Bun'ei]] 5 (1268), he handled the shogunate’s response to envoys from the [[Yuan dynasty]].<ref>『史料綜覧』第5編之905 144頁</ref> Shortly before the {{ill|Mongol invasions of Japan|ja|元寇|12=draft|12=draft}} (Bun'ei Campaign), Sukeyoshi took religious vows, adopting the name Kakue, and passed his leadership to his eldest son, {{ill|Shōni Kyonori|ja|少弐経資|12=draft|12=draft}}. Despite his age, Sukeyoshi personally led the Kyushu defense forces and successfully repelled the invading Yuan forces.
In [[Kōan]] 4 (1281), Sukeyoshi participated in the {{ill|Second Mongol invasion of Japan|ja|弘安の役|12=draft|12=draft}}. He fought valiantly in the {{ill|Battle of Iki Island|ja|壱岐島の戦い|12=draft|12=draft}}, driving the Yuan forces off Iki Island.<ref>『史料綜覧』第5編之905 258頁</ref> However, he succumbed to injuries sustained in the campaign and died shortly afterward at the age of 84. His funeral was conducted by {{ill|Daionkokushi|ja|大応国師南浦紹明|12=draft|12=draft}} at {{ill|Sōfuku-ji (Fukuoka)|ja|崇福寺|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Dazaifu|ja|太宰府|12=draft|12=draft}}.
In [[Ninji]] 3 (1242), Sukeyoshi donated land to establish the {{ill|Shōten-ji|ja|承天寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Hakata|ja|博多|12=draft|12=draft}}, fulfilling a promise made by his father, {{ill|Muto Sukeyori|ja|武藤資頼|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>渡辺文吉『武藤少弐興亡史』 海鳥社、1989th year (p.12)</ref>
Near the ruins of {{ill|Anyo-ji|ja|安養寺|12=draft|12=draft}}, one of the {{ill|Kannon-ji Temple|ja|観世音寺四十九子院跡|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Dazaifu|ja|太宰府市|12=draft|12=draft}}, the burial site of Sukeyoshi is marked by a {{ill|Hōkyōintō|ja|宝篋印塔|1=Hōkyōintō|2=ja|3=宝篋印塔|4=fr|5=Hōkyōintō|6=nl|7=Hōkyōintō|1=Hōkyōintō|1=Hōkyōintō|12=draft|12=draft}} memorial alongside a five-tiered pagoda for Sukeyori.<ref>[https://www.kyuhaku.jp/dazaifu/d-map/kaisetu26.html 九州国立博物館「西都 大宰府」記述あり。]</ref>
