'''Shōni Sukeyoshi''' (少弐 資能) was a [[samurai]] and retainer of the [[Kamakura shogunate]] active during the early to mid-[[Kamakura period]]. He was the second head of the {{ill|Shōni clan|ja|少弐氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōni clan|qq=}}.
== Biography ==
During Sukeyoshi’s time, the {{ill|Muto clan|ja|武藤氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muto clan|qq=}} held the position of [[Dazai Shōni]], a role associated with governance in the {{ill|Dazaifu|ja|大宰府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dazaifu|qq=}} region. This responsibility led to the family adopting the surname {{ill|Shōni|ja|少弐氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōni|qq=}} starting from Sukeyoshi’s generation.
Sukeyoshi wielded significant power in northern Kyushu and served as the shogunate's {{ill|Chinzei Bugyō|ja|鎮西奉行|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinzei Bugyō|qq=}}. In [[Bun'ei]] 5 (1268), he handled the shogunate’s response to envoys from the [[Yuan dynasty]].<ref>『史料綜覧』第5編之905 144頁</ref> Shortly before the {{ill|Mongol invasions of Japan|ja|元寇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mongol invasions of Japan|qq=}} (Bun'ei Campaign), Sukeyoshi took religious vows, adopting the name Kakue, and passed his leadership to his eldest son, {{ill|Shōni Kyonori|ja|少弐経資|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōni Kyonori|qq=}}. Despite his age, Sukeyoshi personally led the Kyushu defense forces and successfully repelled the invading Yuan forces.
In [[Kōan]] 4 (1281), Sukeyoshi participated in the {{ill|Second Mongol invasion of Japan|ja|弘安の役|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Second Mongol invasion of Japan|qq=}}. He fought valiantly in the {{ill|Battle of Iki Island|ja|壱岐島の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Iki Island|qq=}}, driving the Yuan forces off Iki Island.<ref>『史料綜覧』第5編之905 258頁</ref> However, he succumbed to injuries sustained in the campaign and died shortly afterward at the age of 84. His funeral was conducted by {{ill|Daionkokushi|ja|大応国師南浦紹明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daionkokushi|qq=}} at {{ill|Sōfuku-ji (Fukuoka)|ja|崇福寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōfuku-ji (Fukuoka)|qq=}}, {{ill|Dazaifu|ja|太宰府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dazaifu|qq=}}.
In [[Ninji]] 3 (1242), Sukeyoshi donated land to establish the {{ill|Shōten-ji|ja|承天寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōten-ji|qq=}} in {{ill|Hakata|ja|博多|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakata|qq=}}, fulfilling a promise made by his father, {{ill|Muto Sukeyori|ja|武藤資頼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muto Sukeyori|qq=}}.<ref>渡辺文吉『武藤少弐興亡史』 海鳥社、1989th year (p.12)</ref>
Near the ruins of {{ill|Anyo-ji|ja|安養寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anyo-ji|qq=}}, one of the {{ill|Kannon-ji Temple|ja|観世音寺四十九子院跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kannon-ji Temple|qq=}} in {{ill|Dazaifu|ja|太宰府市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dazaifu|qq=}}, the burial site of Sukeyoshi is marked by a {{ill|Hōkyōintō|ja|宝篋印塔|1=Hōkyōintō|2=ja|3=宝篋印塔|4=fr|5=Hōkyōintō|6=nl|7=Hōkyōintō|1=Hōkyōintō|1=Hōkyōintō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōkyōintō|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōkyōintō|qq=}} memorial alongside a five-tiered pagoda for Sukeyori.<ref>[https://www.kyuhaku.jp/dazaifu/d-map/kaisetu26.html 九州国立博物館「西都 大宰府」記述あり。]</ref>
